#Text=Women 's March becomes largest protest in U.S. history
#Text=Tuesday , January 24 , 2017

#Text=On Saturday , by estimates , over 500,000 women and other protesters — twice the figure expected by organizers — marched through Washington D.C. to protest the inauguration of Donald Trump as president of the United States .
#Text=They were accompanied by hundreds of thousands of others in hundreds of sister marches in cities across the United States and on all seven continents , including Antarctica .
#Text=The main march in Washington D.C. drew over half a million people .
#Text=Image : Ted Eytan ( Flickr ) .

#Text=Though different publications are providing different figures , The Independent reports that between 3.3 and 4.6 million people walked and carried signs , 750,000 in Los Angeles , 575,000 in Washington D.C. , 450,000 in New York , 250,000 in Chicago and many smaller figures in other cities , making this the largest protest in American history .
#Text=In contrast to the protests on the day of the inauguration , not one marcher was reported arrested in Washington D.C. , Los Angeles , New York , Chicago or Seattle .
#Text=At the march , women , men and children chanted slogans like " This is what democracy looks like !

#Text=" and carried signs evoking images from Rosie the Riveter to Princess Leia or referenced things that Trump had said during his campaign , as in " Fury coming out my wherever " and " Hands too small ca n't build a wall .
#Text="

#Text= Senior counselor at the Albright Stonebridge Group and former U.S. undersecretary of state for political affairs Wendy R. Sherman wrote in USA Today , " For me , the agenda is clear .

column1: #Text=It is solidarity .
#Text=It is saying to the new administration that misogyny cannot rule .

#Text=Whether reproductive rights , equal pay for equal work , an end to sexual violence , women in combat or the importance of girls ' education worldwide , we are here ; we will not relent ; we will not give up .
#Text="
